### Sealed in C#

The `sealed` keyword prevents inheritance for classes or further overriding of methods/properties.

### Sealed Classes

A sealed class cannot be used as a base class:

```csharp
public sealed class SecurityManager
{
    public void Authenticate() { }
}

// public class CustomSecurity : SecurityManager { }  // Error
```

### Sealed Methods

Prevent further overriding of a virtual method:

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual void Show() { }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public sealed override void Show() { }
}

public class MoreDerived : Derived
{
    // public override void Show() { }  // Error - sealed
}
```

### Sealed Properties

```csharp
public class Base
{
    public virtual string Name { get; set; }
}

public class Derived : Base
{
    public sealed override string Name { get; set; }
}
```

### Why Use Sealed?

| Reason | Benefit |
|--------|---------|
| Security | Prevents malicious inheritance |
| Performance | Enables compiler optimizations |
| Design | Intent is clear - no extension |
| Safety | Prevents breaking subclass behavior |

### Common Sealed Types in .NET

```csharp
sealed class String
sealed class Int32
sealed class Double
sealed class Boolean
```

### Sealed vs Static Classes

| Aspect | Sealed Class | Static Class |
|--------|--------------|--------------|
| Can be instantiated | Yes | No |
| Can have instance members | Yes | No |
| Can inherit | No (sealed) | No (static) |
| Can be inherited from | No | No |
| Use case | Prevent extension | Utility classes |

### Static Sealed Class

All static classes are implicitly sealed:

```csharp
public static class MathHelper
{
    public static double Square(double x) => x * x;
}
// Equivalent: static classes are always sealed
```

### Record and Sealed

Records can be sealed:

```csharp
public sealed record Point(int X, int Y);
// Cannot derive from Point
```

> **Key Point:** Use `sealed` when you want to prevent inheritance for security, performance, or design reasons. Sealing a method prevents further overrides in derived classes. The compiler can optimize virtual calls for sealed classes.

### Performance Benefit

```csharp
// Without sealed - virtual call overhead
public class Base { public virtual void Foo() { } }

// With sealed - can be devirtualized
public sealed class Derived : Base { public override void Foo() { } }
```

### When NOT to Seal

- Library/framework code where extension is expected
- When the Open/Closed principle favors extension
- When you cannot predict future requirements

codeExample:
using System;

public class Account
{
    public virtual void Display() => Console.WriteLine("Account");
}

public class SavingsAccount : Account
{
    public sealed override void Display()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Savings Account - cannot override further");
    }
}

// public class PremiumAccount : SavingsAccount
// {
//     public override void Display() { }  // Error - sealed
// }

sealed class Configuration
{
    public string ConnectionString { get; init; }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var config = new Configuration { ConnectionString = "Server=local;" };
        Console.WriteLine(config.ConnectionString);
    }
}
